@node "SysEdDoors" "Doors"


                             @{b}SystemEditor: Doors
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

@{u}Introduction@{uu}

Here you can configure doors to make them available to the BBS.

              @{"     Door Call Name     " link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"} @{"    Interf.Mod.Types    " link "SEDoorsInterfModTypes"}
              @{" BBSCMD/SYSCMD/CONFxCMD " link "SEDoorsBBSCMDSYSCMDCONFxCMD"} @{"   Single/Multi Node    " link "SEDoorsSingleMultiNode"}
              @{"          Conf          " link "SEDoorsConf"} @{"      Door Config       " link "SEDoorsDoorConfig"}
              @{"       Door Path        " link "SEDoorsDoorPath"} @{"           NR           " link "SEDoorsNR"}
              @{"       Stack Size       " link "SEDoorsStackSize"} @{"           NC           " link "SEDoorsNC"}
              @{"      Access Level      " link "SEDoorsAccessLevel"} @{"           CF           " link "SEDoorsCF"}
              @{"        Priority        " link "SEDoorsPriority"} @{"           SR           " link "SEDoorsSR"}
              @{"        Password        " link "SEDoorsPassword"} @{"           SC           " link "SEDoorsSC"}
              @{"     Name at Server     " link "SEDoorsNameatServer"} @{"           AR           " link "SEDoorsAR"}
              @{"        Internal        " link "SEDoorsInternal"} @{"           AC           " link "SEDoorsAC"}
              @{"     Menu (Beware)      " link "SEDoorsMenuBeware"} @{"           RD           " link "SEDoorsRD"}
              @{"     Intern/MenuCmd     " link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"} @{"         UNUSED         " link "SEDoorsUNUSED"}

                          @{"          SAVE          " link "SEDoorsSAVE"}
                          @{"         RENAME         " link "SEDoorsRENAME"}
                          @{"          BACK          " link "SEDoorsBACK"}
                          @{"         REMOVE         " link "SEDoorsREMOVE"}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsDoorCallName" "Door Call Name"


                     @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Door Call Name
                    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

This is the name which is used to start a door.
The door configuration will also be saved under the same name.

You can also use the pop up gadget to load a door configuration.

You can type a door call name in this gadget and if there is already a
door config file with this name this will automaticly loaded, but it is
dependant on the position of the cycle gadget: @{"BBSCMD/SYSCMD/CONFxCMD" link "SEDoorsBBSCMDSYSCMDCONFxCMD"}
from where the SystemEditor loads the configuration.

If you want to enter a new door config entry just write a name here which
should be used to call the door from the bbs.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsBBSCMDSYSCMDCONFxCMD" "BBSCMD/SYSCMD/CONFxCMD"


                 @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): BBSCMD/SYSCMD/CONFxCMD
                ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

There are different possibilities to start a door:

 - BBSCMD is global and can be accessed by typing the @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"} in the menu
          prompt or via MCI commandos.

 - SYSCMD can't be used directly from a user. The node will start doors at
          different positions in the node. For example EXAMINE after a
          file transfer.

 - CONF<x>CMD is nearly the same as BBSCMD, but is local and only available
              in one conference which is described with <x>.This means the type for
              <x> the conference number in the gadget @{"Conf" link "SEDoorsConf"}.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsConf" "Conf"


                          @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Conf
                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The conference number used if @{"BBSCMD/SYSCMD/CONFxCMD" link "SEDoorsBBSCMDSYSCMDCONFxCMD"} is on CONFxCMD.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsDoorPath" "Door Path"


                        @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Door Path
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Here must be the complete path to the door, except if you have a door loaded
resident type only the name of the resident door.

You can also use the pop up gadget to get the door location.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsStackSize" "Stack Size"


                       @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Stack Size
                      ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The stack size for the door.

Some doors are needing more than 4096 bytes stack, here you can raise the
stack. Look in the document of the door to see how much stack it needs.

Default is 0 and means the System will give the door a stack of 4096 bytes
as default.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsAccessLevel" "Access Level"


                      @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Access Level
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The level a user must have to start this door.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsPriority" "Priority"


                        @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Priority
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The priority a door should run with.

Default is 0 and this is normally the best priority you should always use.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsPassword" "Password"


                        @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Password
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

A password the user must type in correctly before the door will be started.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsNameatServer" "Name at Server"


                     @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Name at Server
                    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

A string which appears in the @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} as action string.

The sysop can easy see which door runs if there is a name of the door.

Note: Don't wonder if this string you typed here doesn't appears in the @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"}
      and an other string appears instead. Every door is able to write his
      own string instead. This gadget is only useful for doors which doesn't
      write a action string in the @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} action.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsInternal" "Internal"


                        @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Internal
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

If you select this gadget most other gadgets are ghosted.

Internal means you can start an internal menu command.
The @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"} is the name a user can type in the menu
and the now available gadget @{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"} is used to be the
replacement for @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}.

Examples:

@{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}: "1"
@{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"}: "J 1"

If you now type "1" internal is it the same as if you had typed "J 1" and you
will join into conference 1.

@{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}: "D"
@{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"}: "D"
@{"Access Level" link "SEDoorsAccessLevel"}  : "200"
@{"Password" link "SEDoorsPassword"}      : "leech"
@{"Name at Server" link "SEDoorsNameatServer"}: "Download PW!"

If you now type "D" internal the "D" command will be started, but before
you must have the level 200 or higher and you have to enter the correct
password: "leech". At the @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} will be the action string: "Download PW!".

Note: Internal will only start internal commands and no doors!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsMenuBeware" "Menu (Beware)"


                      @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Menu (Beware)
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

If you select this gadget most otehr gadgets are ghosted.

Menu means you can start a menu command. This can be an internal menu command
or a door.
The @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"} is the name a user can type in the menu
and the now available gadget @{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"} is used to be the
replacement for @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}.

Examples:

@{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}: "1"
@{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"}: "J 1"

If you now type "1" internal is it the same as if you had typed "J 1" and you
will join into conference 1.

@{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}: "D"
@{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"}: "U"
@{"Name at Server" link "SEDoorsNameatServer"}: "No Downloads!"

If you now type "D" internal the "U" command will be started.
At the @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} will be the action string: "No Downloads!".

Note: Menu will also start doors!!! Beware that you enter no dead loops!
      You *MUSN'T* have the same name for @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"} and
      @{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"}.

Example:

@{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"}: "D"
@{"Intern/MenuCmd" link "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd"}: "D"

This is very dangerous because "D" is a "Menu kind" and will start "D"
again means it will start itself in a loop.

Also beware of cross calls like "D" calls "U" and "U" calls "D"!!!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsInternMenuCmd" "Intern/MenuCmd"


                     @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Intern/MenuCmd
                    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Here you can type what should be started/executed if you have selected
@{"Internal" link "SEDoorsInternal"} or @{"Menu (Beware)" link "SEDoorsMenuBeware"}.

You can type here an internal menu command or door and you can type
aguments as well.

Example:

"N S U" and for @{"Door Call Name" link "SEDoorsDoorCallName"} "NEW".

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsInterfModTypes" "Interf.Mod.Types"


                 @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Interface Module Types
                ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The Interface Module Types are used to identify the kinf of the door:

 - FIM = FAME Interface Module (FAME doors)
         The FAME door standard is the most complex one of all with
         more then 1000 commands overall and more than 400 available
         ones for every one who wants to write doors for FAME.

 - XIM = Express Interface Module

 - TIM = Traditional Interface Module (Paragon doors) (You need ParaDoor)

 - AIM = Arexx Interface Module (You need RexxDoor)

 - CIM = Compiled (Arexx) Interface Module (You need RexxExec)

 - RIM = Rexx Interface Module (Arexx scripts)

         Not implemented yet!

 - SIM = Script Interface Module (DOS scripts)

         Not implemented yet!

 - TXT = View text file
         To view a text file and this also with MCI commands in it.

         Not implemented yet!

 - SND = Play a sample

         Not implemented yet!

 - SPK = Speak via narrator.device

         Not implemented yet!

 - GFM = Graphic Module
         A graphic standard which is not realized yet and will take much
         time to realize, because this one should do everything and should
         be maybe an xem emulation library.
         This graphic standard shall be a mix of RIP, Hydra, WWW (HTML),
         CompuServe and much more. With gadgets, text, graphics, pictures
         and interfaces for protocols and online games etc.
         The idea is available, but we have not time to implement this now
         and are looking for some coders which are willing to do this.

         Not implemented yet!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEDoorsSingleMultiNode" "Single/Multi Node"


                    @{b}SystemEditor (Doors): Single/Multi Node
                   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Multi Node doors are most available, but there are SingleĀNode Doors too.
If you have a single node door, a door which isn't able to run on multi node
systems like some Paragon Doors, you have to use Single Node here.

@endnode

